entries.meaning: The amount by which something overruns.
examples: At least this year's overrun isn't as unmanageable as last year!

entries.meaning: (aviation) An area of terrain beyond the end of a runway that is kept flat and unobstructed to allow an aircraft that runs off the end of the runway to stop safely.
examples: The runway has 7,000 feet of paved surface, plus a 2,000-foot grass overrun.

entries.meaning: (food) Air that is whipped into a frozen dessert to make it easier to serve and eat.

verbs.description: overrun (third-person singular simple present overruns, present participle overrunning, simple past overran, past participle overrun)

entries.meaning: To defeat an enemy and invade in great numbers, seizing the enemy positions conclusively.
To infest, swarm over, flow over.
examples: The vine overran its trellis; the field is overrun with weeds.

definitionGroups.group: To run past; to run beyond.

entries.meaning: To run past the end of.
examples: The aircraft didn't stop in time and overran the runway.
The performance overran by ten minutes, which caused some people to miss their bus home.

entries.meaning: (printing) To carry (some type, a line or column, etc.) backward or forward into an adjacent line or page.
To go beyond; to extend in part beyond.
examples: In machinery, a sliding piece is said to overrun its bearing when its forward end goes beyond it.

entries.meaning: To abuse or oppress, as if by treading upon.
